40 SECTION 15. G.S. 15A-1415 reads as rewritten:
41 "§ 15A-1415. Grounds for appropriate relief which may be asserted by defendant after
42 verdict; limitation as to time.
43 (a) At any time after verdict, a noncapital defendant by motion may seek appropriate
44 relief upon any of the grounds enumerated in this section. In a capital case, a postconviction
45 motion for appropriate relief shall be filed within 120 days from the latest of the following:
46 (1) The court's judgment has been filed, but the defendant failed to perfect a
47 timely appeal;
48 (2) The mandate issued by a court of the appellate division on direct appeal
49 pursuant to N.C.R. App. P. 32(b) and the time for filing a petition for writ of
Page 4 Senate Bill 94-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 certiorari to the United States Supreme Court has expired without a petition
2 being filed;
3 (3) The United States Supreme Court denied a timely petition for writ of certiorari
4 of the decision on direct appeal by the Supreme Court of North Carolina;
5 (4) Following the denial of discretionary review by the Supreme Court of North
6 Carolina, the United States Supreme Court denied a timely petition for writ of
7 certiorari seeking review of the decision on direct appeal by the North
8 Carolina Court of Appeals;
9 (5) The United States Supreme Court granted the defendant's or the State's timely
10 petition for writ of certiorari of the decision on direct appeal by the Supreme
11 Court of North Carolina or North Carolina Court of Appeals, but subsequently
12 left the defendant's conviction and sentence undisturbed; or
13 (6) The appointment of postconviction counsel for an indigent capital defendant.
14 …
15 (c) Notwithstanding the time limitations herein, a defendant at any time after verdict may
16 by a motion for appropriate relief, raise the ground that evidence is available which was unknown
17 or unavailable to the defendant at the time of trial, which could not with due diligence have been
18 discovered or made available at that time, including recanted testimony, and which has a direct
19 and material bearing upon the defendant's eligibility for the death penalty or the defendant's guilt
20 or innocence. A motion based upon such newly discovered evidence must be filed within a
21 reasonable time of its discovery.
22 …."
23 SECTION 16. G.S. 15A-1419(e) reads as rewritten:
24 "(e) For the purposes of subsection (b) of this section, a fundamental miscarriage of justice
25 only results if:
26 (1) The defendant establishes that more likely than not, but for the error, no
27 reasonable fact finder would have found the defendant guilty of the underlying
28 offense; oroffense.
29 (2) The defendant establishes by clear and convincing evidence that, but for the
30 error, no reasonable fact finder would have found the defendant eligible for
31 the death penalty.
32 A defendant raising a claim of newly discovered evidence of factual innocence or ineligibility
33 for the death penalty, otherwise barred by the provisions of subsection (a) of this section or
34 G.S. 15A-1415(c), may only show a fundamental miscarriage of justice by proving by clear and
35 convincing evidence that, in light of the new evidence, if credible, no reasonable juror would
36 have found the defendant guilty beyond a reasonable doubt or eligible for the death penalty."
37 SECTION 17. Subchapter XV of Chapter 15A of the General Statutes is repealed.
38 SECTION 18. G.S. 90-1.1(5) reads as rewritten:
39 "(5) The practice of medicine or surgery. – Except as otherwise provided by this
40 subdivision, the practice of medicine or surgery, for purposes of this Article,
41 includes any of the following acts:
42 a. Advertising, holding out to the public, or representing in any manner
43 that the individual is authorized to practice medicine in this State.
44 b. Offering or undertaking to prescribe, order, give, or administer any
45 drug or medicine for the use of any other individual.
46 c. Offering or undertaking to prevent or diagnose, correct, prescribe for,
47 administer to, or treat in any manner or by any means, methods, or
48 devices any disease, illness, pain, wound, fracture, infirmity, defect, or
49 abnormal physical or mental condition of any individual, including the
50 management of pregnancy or parturition.
